lia}}\n{{Articles on first-level administrative divisions of Oceanian countries}}\n{{Australia topics}}\n\n<!--Categories-->\n[[Category:Australia geography-related lists]]\n[[Category:Country subdivisions in Oceania|Australia 1]]\n[[Category:First-level administrative country subdivisions|States, Australia]]\n[[Category:Lists of subdivisions of Australia|Australia, States and territories]]\n[[Category:States and territories of Australia| ]]\n[[Category:Subdivisions of Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|First-level subdivision of Australia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox subdivision type\n| name               = Australian states and territories\n| alt_name           = \n| map                = Map_of_Australia.png\n| category           = Federation:\n*[[Federated states|States]] (6)\n*[[Federal territory|Internal territories]] (3)\n*[[Territory#Overseas territory|External territories]] (7)\n| territory          = [[Australia|Commonwealth of Australia]]\n| start_date         = \n| current_number     = \n| number_date        = \n| population_range   = <small> Two territories are uninhabited: [[Ashmore and Cartier Islands|Ashmore&nbsp;&&nbsp;Cartier Islands]] and [[Heard Island and McDonald Islands|Heard&nbsp;&&nbsp;McDonald Islands]].<br>The most populous state/territory is [[New South Wales]], with 7,955,900 people (2016).</small>\n| area_range         = <small> The smallest territory is the [[Cocos (Keeling) Islands]] with an area of {{Convert|14|km2|abbr=on}}.<br>The largest state/territory is the [[Australian Antarctic Territory]], which is {{Convert|5896500|km2|abbr=on}}.</small>\n| government         = \n| subdivision        = [[Local government in Australia|Local government areas]]<br />[[Lands administrative divisions of Australia|Cadastral divisions]]\n}}\n\nGovernment in the [[Australia|Commonwealth of Australia]] is exercised on three levels: [[Government of Australia|federal]], '''states and territories''', and [[local government in Australia|local government]].\n\nThere are six '''states''':  [[New South Wales]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Queensland]], [[Western Australia]], [[South Australia]] and [[Tasmania]]. Historically, each is a successor to one of the previous [[Australian colonies]]. Each state has its own constitution, with its own legislature (parliament), judiciary and executive.  The state parliaments have [[plenary power|plenary]] legislative power, except that some areas of legislative power are exclusive to the Federal Parliament, many others are exercised concurrently with it and, in case of conflict between federal and state legislation, the federal legislation prevails.  A decision of a state judiciary is subject to appeal to the [[High Court of Australia|High Court]].\n\nThere are also ten '''territories''', whose existence and governmental structure (if any) depend on federal legislation.  The territories are distinguished for federal administrative purposes between ''internal'' territories, i.e. those within the Australian mainland, and ''external'' territories, although the differences among all the territories relate to population rather than location.\n\nTwo of the three ''internal'' territories{{mdash}}the [[Australian Capital Territory]] (ACT), which was established to be a neutral site of the federal capital, and the [[Northern Territory]]{{mdash}}function almost as states.  Each has self-government, through its legislative assembly, but the assembly's legislation can be federally overridden.  Each has its own judiciary, with appeal to a federal court.  The third internal territory, the [[Jervis Bay Territory]], is the product of Australia's complex relationship with its capital city; rather than having the same level of autonomy as the other internal territories, it has services provided by the ACT.\n\nThere are also seven ''external'' territories, not part of the Australian mainland or of any state. Three of them have a small permanent population, two have tiny and transient populations, and two are uninhabited.  All are directly administered by the federal [[Department of Infrastructure, Regional Development and Cities]] (or the [[Department of the Environment and Energy]] in the case of the [[Australian Antarctic Territory]]). [[Norfolk Island]], which is permanently populated, was partially self-governing until 2015.\n\nThe term \"'''interstate'''\" is used within Australia to refer to any cross-border events, transactions, or travel.\n\n== Geographic Australia ==\nThe term ''geographic Australia'' is used by the Australian government to describe the area covered by demographic statistics such as national population figures. This area comprises [[Christmas Island]] and the [[Cocos (Keeling) Islands]] in addition to the six states and three mainland territories; Norfolk Island is the only territory with a permanent population that is not part of geographic Australia.<ref>{{Cite report | first=Brian | last=Pink | authorlink=Brian_Pink  | year=2010  | title=Australian Standard Geographical Classification (ASGC) | publisher=Australian Bureau of Statistics | section=Definition of Australia | sectionurl=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/0/58B39EB886CFC607CA25779F00172F75?opendocument | page=5}}</ref>\n\n== States and territories ==\n{{Administrative divisions of Australia}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%\"\n|-\n|+ style=\"text-align:center;background:#BFD7FF\"| Reference map for states and territories of Australia\n|-\n|[[File:Australia states and territories labelled.svg|frameless|upright=2.75]]\n|}\n{{anchor|Table}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ style=\"text-align:center;background:#BFD7FF\"| States of Australia<ref group=\"n\">Unless provided, references and details on data provided in the table can be found within the individual state and territory articles.</ref>\n|-\n!class=\"unsortable\"|[[List of Australian flags#States and territories|Flag]]\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\"|State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"45\"|Postal\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"45\"|[[ISO 3166-2:AU|ISO]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[ISO 3166-2:AU]] ([[International Organization for Standardization|ISO]] [[ISO 3166-2|3166-2]] codes for the states and territories of Australia)</ref>\n![[List of Australian capital cities|Capital]]\n!Population<br />(Jun&nbsp;2019)<ref name=ABSQPOP>{{cite web |url=http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/mf/3101.0 | title = 3101.0 \u2013 Australian Demographic Statistics, Jun 2019| accessdate = 20 January 2020 | publisher= [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] | date = 19 December 2019}}</ref>\n!Area (km\u00b2)<ref name=\"GAarea\">{{cite web|title=Area of Australia \u2013 States and Territories|url=http://www.ga.gov.au/scientific-topics/national-location-information/dimensions/area-of-australia-states-and-territories|website=Geoscience Australia: National Location Information|publisher=[[Geoscience Australia]]|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n![[Governors of the Australian states|Governor]]\n!colspan=2|[[Premiers and chief ministers of the Australian states and territories|Premier]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n| {{flagg|pxx|New South Wales|size=100px}} ||style=\"text-align:left\"| '''[[New South Wales]]''' || NSW || AU-NSW ||style=\"text-align:left\"| [[Sydney]] ||style=\"text-align:right\"| {{nts|8089526}} ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 809,952\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Margaret Beazley]]\n|style=\"background-color: {{Liberal Party of Australia/meta/color}}\" |\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Gladys Berejiklian]]<br />([[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]])\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n| {{flagg|pxx|Queensland|size=100px}} ||style=\"text-align:left\"| '''[[Queensland]]''' || QLD || AU-QLD ||style=\"text-align:left\"| [[Brisbane]] ||style=\"text-align:right\"| {{nts|5095100}} ||style=\"text-align:right\"| 1,851,736\n|style=\"text-align:left\