{"title_page": "Wilson's Raid", "text_new": "{{Campaignbox Wilson's Raid in Alabama and Georgia}}\n'''Wilson's Raid''' was a [[cavalry]] operation through [[Alabama]] and [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] in March&ndash;April 1865, late in the [[American Civil War]]. [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brig. Gen.]] [[James H. Wilson]] led his [[Union Army]] Cavalry Corps to destroy [[Southern United States|Southern]] manufacturing facilities and was opposed unsuccessfully by a much smaller force under [[Confederate States Army|Confederate]] [[Lieutenant General (CSA)|Lt. Gen.]] [[Nathan Bedford Forrest]].\n\n==Background and opposing forces==\nAfter his victory at the [[Battle of Nashville]], Union [[Major general (United States)|Maj. Gen.]] [[George H. Thomas]] and his [[Army of the Cumberland]] found themselves with virtually no organized military opposition in the heart of the South. Thomas ordered Brig. Gen. James H. Wilson (who commanded the Cavalry Corps of the [[Military Division of the Mississippi]], but was attached to Thomas's army) to lead a [[Raid (military)|raid]] to destroy the [[arsenal]] at [[Selma, Alabama]], in conjunction with Maj. Gen. [[Edward Canby]]'s operations against [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]]. Selma was strategically important as one of the few Confederate military bases remaining in Southern hands. The town contained an arsenal, a [[Confederate Navy|naval]] [[foundry]], gun factories, a [[Gunpowder|powder]] mill, military warehouses, and railroad repair shops.\n\nWilson led approximately 13,500 men in three divisions, commanded by Brig. Gens. [[Edward M. McCook]], [[Eli Long]], and [[Emory Upton]]. Each cavalryman was armed with the formidable 7-shot [[Spencer repeating rifle]]. His principal opponent was Lt. Gen. Nathan Bedford Forrest, whose Cavalry Corps of the Department of Alabama, Mississippi, and East Louisiana consisted of about 2,500 troopers organized into two small divisions, led by Brig. Gens. [[James R. Chalmers]] and [[William Hicks Jackson|William H. Jackson]], two partial brigades under Brig. Gen. [[Philip D. Roddey]] and Colonel [[Edward Crossland]], and a few local [[Militia (United States)|militia]].\n\n==Raid==\nWilson was delayed in crossing the rain-swollen [[Tennessee River]], but he got underway on March 22, 1865, departing from Gravelly Springs in [[Lauderdale County, Alabama]]. He sent his forces in three separate columns to mask his intentions and confuse the enemy; Forrest learned very late in the raid that Selma was the primary target. Minor skirmishes occurred at [[Houston, Alabama|Houston]] (March 25) and [[Black Warrior River]] (March 26), and Wilson's columns rejoined at [[Jasper, Alabama|Jasper]] on March 27.\n\n[[File:University of Alabama 1859.jpg|thumb|400px|View of [[University of Alabama Quad|the Quad]] at the [[University of Alabama]] in 1859. The Rotunda can be seen at center, with the halls visible in the background.  All of these buildings were destroyed during Wilson's Raid on April 4, 1865.]]\nOn March 28, at [[Elyton]], in present-day [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], another skirmish occurred and the Union troopers destroyed the Oxmoor and Irondale iron furnaces. A detachment of General Emory Upton's division destroyed the C.B. Churchill and Company foundry in [[Columbiana, Alabama|Columbiana]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iuZYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=cb+churchill+columbiana+alabama&source=bl&ots=uKrm8SpCQ0&sig=ciGIQd6G_kXFr2k-ONjyFjYc-UQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=e0GgU86SKYewyASozILwDA&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=cb%20churchill%20columbiana%20alabama&f=false |title=The story of coal and iron in Alabama - Ethel Armes - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-17}}</ref> and the [[Shelby Iron Company|Shelby Iron Works]] in [[Shelby, Alabama|Shelby]] on March 31, 1865.<ref>http://www.bhamwiki.com/wiki/index.php?title=Shelby_Furnace</ref>\n\n===Tuscaloosa===\nWilson also detached a 1,500 man brigade under Brig. Gen. [[John T. Croxton]] and sent them south and west to burn the [[Roupes Valley Ironworks]] at [[Tannehill Ironworks|Tannehill]] and [[Brierfield Furnace|Bibb Naval Furnace]] at [[Brierfield, Alabama|Brierfield]] on March 31. They then burned the [[University of Alabama]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], which was a prominent military school, on April 4.<ref>Jones, p. 60</ref> This movement diverted Chalmer's division away from Forrest's main force.\n\n===Selma===\nOn March 31, Forrest was routed by the larger, better-armed Union force at [[Montevallo, Alabama|Montevallo]]. The cavalrymen under Chalmers had not arrived to reinforce Forrest, but he could not wait. During the action, Forrest's headquarters were overrun and documents captured that gave valuable intelligence concerning his plans. Wilson dispatched McCook to link up with Croxton's brigade at [[Vance, Alabama|Trion]] (now Vance) and then led the remainder of his force rapidly toward Selma. Forrest made a stand on April 1 at [[Plantersville, Alabama|Plantersville]], near Ebenezer Church, and was routed once again at the [[Battle of Ebenezer Church]]. The Confederates raced toward Selma and deployed into a three-mile, semicircular defensive line anchored at both ends by the [[Alabama River]].\n\nThe [[Battle of Selma]] took place on April 2. The divisions of Long and Upton assaulted Forrest's hastily constructed works. The dismounted Union troopers broke through by afternoon, after brief periods of [[hand-to-hand combat]]; the inexperienced militiamen abandoning their positions and fleeing was the primary reason for the entire line breaking. General Wilson personally led a mounted charge of the [[4th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|4th U.S. Cavalry]] against an unfinished portion of the line. General Long was severely wounded in the head during the assault. Forrest, who was also wounded, and whose tiny corps was severely damaged, regrouped at [[Marion, Alabama|Marion]], where he finally rejoined Chalmers. Wilson's men worked for over a week at destroying military facilities.  From there, Wilson's forces moved toward [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], which they occupied on April 12.\n\n===West Point===\nDespite [[Robert E. Lee]]'s April 9 surrender of the [[Army of Northern Virginia]] following the [[Battle of Appomattox Court House]], the [[Army of Tennessee]] under the command of Gen [[Joseph E. Johnston]] had not yet surrendered the Confederate forces in the Carolinas, Georgia, and Florida.  Wilson's plan was to head east into Georgia to destroy the remaining arsenals and munitions, and to cause any remaining local forces to \"disintegrate.\"<ref>Jones, pp. 117-8</ref> Wilson's success in this plan would be accelerated if his forces could secure at least one of several key bridges over the Chattahoochee River.  One such bridge led into the town of West Point. To avoid any delay in the raid, Wilson separated his force sending a 3,700-man detachment under Colonel [[Oscar Hugh La Grange]] to capture both the bridge and the town.<ref>\"Out of the Storm: The End of the Civil War, April\u2013June 1865\" by Noah Andre Trudeau</ref>  Simultaneously, Wilson ordered Upton's division to rush toward another strategically important bridge at Columbus, Georgia. \n\nThe [[Battle of West Point]], Georgia, was fought on Easter Sunday, April 16, when Colonel [[Oscar Hugh La Grange]]'s brigade attacked an earthwork defensive position named Fort Tyler that was defended by a couple hundred young men and teenaged Confederates under CS Brig. Gen. [[Robert C. Tyler]]. Determined to fight to the last ditch, the Confederates fought a wave of dismounted Union troops. The Confederates did not stand a chance as they were largely outnumbered and poorly armed, whereas the Federals were armed with repeaters. The Union soldiers crossed over a ditch while the rebels hurled primitive hand-grenades and fired their weapons.<ref>Trudeau, pp. 253-54</ref> Although the Union men had to assault under the fire of one 32-pounder gun and two 12-pounders inside the earthwork, the fort was captured. Confederate Brig. Gen. [[Robert C. Tyler]] was mortally wounded by a sharpshooter, becoming the last general officer to be killed in the Civil War.\n\nThe defense of West Point was doomed to fail, and had done so. With rebel prisoners, the fort, and bridge in his hands, La Grange moved out to rejoin Wilson. The battle had been won for the Union at a cost of 36 casualties both killed and wounded. The Confederates had lost 18 men killed, 28 wounded, and the remainder captured. With most of the dead southerners in the fort, one Yankee artilleryman said the dead Confederates wore \"an awful look.\"<ref>Trudeau, pp. 254</ref>\n\n===Columbus===\nIn a separate battle on Easter Sunday, April 16, Wilson was victorious in the [[Battle of Columbus, Georgia]], in which Upton's division clashed with Confederate forces at [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus]], capturing the city and its naval works and burning, then scuttling the incomplete [[ironclad]] [[Naval ram|ram]], [[CSS Muscogee|CSS ''Jackson'']]. This engagement is widely regarded as the \"Last Battle of the Civil War.\"<ref>[http://freepages.history.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~bellware/ Civil War Times, April 2003]</ref><ref>[http://freepages.history.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~bellware/paper.html \"The Last Battle of The Civil War,\" by Charles Swift.]</ref> On April 20, Wilson's men captured [[Macon, Georgia]], without resistance, and Wilson's Raid came to an end.  This was only six days before General [[Joseph E. Johnston]]'s surrender of all Confederate troops in the Carolinas, Georgia, and Florida to [[William Tecumseh Sherman]], in North Carolina.\n\n==Aftermath and capture of Jefferson Davis==\nWilson's Raid had been a spectacular success. His men captured five fortified cities, 288 cannons, and 6,820 prisoners, at a cost of 725 Union casualties. Forrest's casualties, from a much smaller force, numbered 1,200. The raid was done without the disastrous [[collateral damage]] that characterized [[Sherman's March to the Sea]] of the previous year. Residents accused Wilson's men of sacking Selma after the battle, but the damage there came from many sources including street combat that continued into the night, as well as 35,000 bales of cotton and the Central Commercial Warehouse fired by Confederates as the city fell.  Some Union soldiers and newly liberated former slaves did engage in plunder.  After the first night, Wilson re-established discipline.<ref>Jones, pp. 92-96</ref>\n\nUpon conclusion of the raid, and following the surrender of all of the Confederate forces east of the [[Chattahoochee River]] by Johnston to Sherman, the hostilities in the theater ended.  However, the pursuit of fleeing officials of the Confederate government commenced as Wilson's forces fanned out through the region.  Confederate President [[Jefferson Davis]] was captured on May 10, 1865, near [[Irwinville, Georgia]].<ref>Jones, pp. 170-176</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* [[David J. Eicher|Eicher, David J.]] ''The Longest Night: A Military History of the Civil War''. New York: Simon & Schuster, 2001. {{ISBN|0-684-84944-5}}.\n* [http://www.nps.gov/hps/abpp/battles/al007.htm National Park Service battle description for Selma]\n* Jones, James Pickett. ''Yankee Blitzkrieg, Wilson's Raid Through Alabama and Georgia''. Athens: University of Georgia Press, 1976. {{ISBN|978-0-8203-0370-3}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aotc.net/Selma.htm Army of the Cumberland website on Wilson's Raid]\n* [http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/face/Article.jsp?id=h-1375 Wilson's Raid article, Encyclopedia of Alabama]\n* [http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/bibb/wilsons-raid-to-macon Wilson's Raid to Macon] historical marker\n\n{{Coord|33.1596|-87.3423|region:US_type:event_scale:10000|display=title}}\n\n{{Alabama in the Civil War}}\n{{Georgia in the Civil War}}\n\n[[Category:Wilson's Raid| ]]\n[[Category:Selma, Alabama]]\n[[Category:History of Columbus, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Cavalry raids of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:1865 in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the American Civil War in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the American Civil War in Alabama]]\n[[Category:1865 in the United States]]\n[[Category:March 1865 events]]\n[[Category:April 1865 events]]\n[[Category:1865 in Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{Campaignbox Wilson's Raid in Alabama and Georgia}}\n'''Wilson's Raid''' was a [[cavalry]] operation through [[Alabama]] and [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] in March&ndash;April 1865, late in the [[American Civil War]]. [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brig. Gen.]] [[James H. Wilson]] led his [[Union Army]] Cavalry Corps to destroy [[Southern United States|Southern]] manufacturing facilities and was opposed unsuccessfully by a much smaller force under [[Confederate States Army|Confederate]] [[Lieutenant General (CSA)|Lt. Gen.]] [[Nathan Bedford Forrest]].\n\n==Background and opposing forces==\nAfter his victory at the [[Battle of Nashville]], Union [[Major general (United States)|Maj. Gen.]] [[George H. Thomas]] and his [[Army of the Cumberland]] found themselves with virtually no organized military opposition in the heart of the South. Thomas ordered Brig. Gen. James H. Wilson (who commanded the Cavalry Corps of the [[Military Division of the Mississippi]], but was attached to Thomas's army) to lead a [[Raid (military)|raid]] to destroy the [[arsenal]] at [[Selma, Alabama]], in conjunction with Maj. Gen. [[Edward Canby]]'s operations against [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]]. Selma was strategically important as one of the few Confederate military bases remaining in Southern hands. The town contained an arsenal, a [[Confederate Navy|naval]] [[foundry]], gun factories, a [[Gunpowder|powder]] mill, military warehouses, and railroad repair shops.\n\nWilson led approximately 13,500 men in three divisions, commanded by Brig. Gens. [[Edward M. McCook]], [[Eli Long]], and [[Emory Upton]]. Each cavalryman was armed with the formidable 7-shot [[Spencer repeating rifle]]. His principal opponent was Lt. Gen. Nathan Bedford Forrest, whose Cavalry Corps of the Department of Alabama, Mississippi, and East Louisiana consisted of about 2,500 troopers organized into two small divisions, led by Brig. Gens. [[James R. Chalmers]] and [[William Hicks Jackson|William H. Jackson]], two partial brigades under Brig. Gen. [[Philip D. Roddey]] and Colonel [[Edward Crossland]], and a few local [[Militia (United States)|militia]].\n\n==Raid==\nWilson was delayed in crossing the rain-swollen [[Tennessee River]], but he got underway on March 22, 1865, departing from Gravelly Springs in [[Lauderdale County, Alabama]]. He sent his forces in three separate columns to mask his intentions and confuse the enemy; Forrest learned very late in the raid that Selma was the primary target. Minor skirmishes occurred at [[Houston, Alabama|Houston]] (March 25) and [[Black Warrior River]] (March 26), and Wilson's columns rejoined at [[Jasper, Alabama|Jasper]] on March 27.\n\n[[File:University of Alabama 1859.jpg|thumb|400px|View of [[University of Alabama Quad|the Quad]] at the [[University of Alabama]] in 1859. The Rotunda can be seen at center, with the halls visible in the background.  All of these buildings were destroyed during Wilson's Raid on April 4, 1865.]]\nOn March 28, at [[Elyton]], in present-day [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], another skirmish occurred and the Union troopers destroyed the Oxmoor and Irondale iron furnaces. A detachment of General Emory Upton's division destroyed the C.B. Churchill and Company foundry in [[Columbiana, Alabama|Columbiana]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iuZYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=cb+churchill+columbiana+alabama&source=bl&ots=uKrm8SpCQ0&sig=ciGIQd6G_kXFr2k-ONjyFjYc-UQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=e0GgU86SKYewyASozILwDA&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=cb%20churchill%20columbiana%20alabama&f=false |title=The story of coal and iron in Alabama - Ethel Armes - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-17}}</ref> and the [[Shelby Iron Company|Shelby Iron Works]] in [[Shelby, Alabama|Shelby]] on March 31, 1865.<ref>http://www.bhamwiki.com/wiki/index.php?title=Shelby_Furnace</ref>\n\n===Tuscaloosa===\nWilson also detached a 1,500 man brigade under Brig. Gen. [[John T. Croxton]] and sent them south and west to burn the [[Roupes Valley Ironworks]] at [[Tannehill Ironworks|Tannehill]] and [[Brierfield Furnace|Bibb Naval Furnace]] at [[Brierfield, Alabama|Brierfield]] on March 31. They then burned the [[University of Alabama]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], which was a prominent military school, on April 4.<ref>Jones, p. 60</ref> This movement diverted Chalmer's division away from Forrest's main force.\n\n===Selma===\nOn March 31, Forrest was routed by the larger, better-armed Union force at [[Montevallo, Alabama|Montevallo]]. The cavalrymen under Chalmers had not arrived to reinforce Forrest, but he could not wait. During the action, Forrest's headquarters were overrun and documents captured that gave valuable intelligence concerning his plans. Wilson dispatched McCook to link up with Croxton's brigade at [[Vance, Alabama|Trion]] (now Vance) and then led the remainder of his force rapidly toward Selma. Forrest made a stand on April 1 at [[Plantersville, Alabama|Plantersville]], near Ebenezer Church, and was routed once again at the [[Battle of Ebenezer Church]]. The Confederates raced toward Selma and deployed into a three-mile, semicircular defensive line anchored at both ends by the [[Alabama River]].\n\nThe [[Battle of Selma]] took place on April 2. The divisions of Long and Upton assaulted Forrest's hastily constructed works. The dismounted Union troopers broke through by afternoon, after brief periods of [[hand-to-hand combat]]; the inexperienced militiamen abandoning their positions and fleeing was the primary reason for the entire line breaking. General Wilson personally led a mounted charge of the 4th U.S. Cavalry against an unfinished portion of the line. General Long was severely wounded in the head during the assault. Forrest, who was also wounded, and whose tiny corps was severely damaged, regrouped at [[Marion, Alabama|Marion]], where he finally rejoined Chalmers. Wilson's men worked for over a week at destroying military facilities.  From there, Wilson's forces moved toward [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], which they occupied on April 12.\n\n===West Point===\nDespite [[Robert E. Lee]]'s April 9 surrender of the [[Army of Northern Virginia]] following the [[Battle of Appomattox Court House]], the [[Army of Tennessee]] under the command of Gen [[Joseph E. Johnston]] had not yet surrendered the Confederate forces in the Carolinas, Georgia, and Florida.  Wilson's plan was to head east into Georgia to destroy the remaining arsenals and munitions, and to cause any remaining local forces to \"disintegrate.\"<ref>Jones, pp. 117-8</ref> Wilson's success in this plan would be accelerated if his forces could secure at least one of several key bridges over the Chattahoochee River.  One such bridge led into the town of West Point. To avoid any delay in the raid, Wilson separated his force sending a 3,700-man detachment under Colonel [[Oscar Hugh La Grange]] to capture both the bridge and the town.<ref>\"Out of the Storm: The End of the Civil War, April\u2013June 1865\" by Noah Andre Trudeau</ref>  Simultaneously, Wilson ordered Upton's division to rush toward another strategically important bridge at Columbus, Georgia. \n\nThe [[Battle of West Point]], Georgia, was fought on Easter Sunday, April 16, when Colonel [[Oscar Hugh La Grange]]'s brigade attacked an earthwork defensive position named Fort Tyler that was defended by a couple hundred young men and teenaged Confederates under CS Brig. Gen. [[Robert C. Tyler]]. Determined to fight to the last ditch, the Confederates fought a wave of dismounted Union troops. The Confederates did not stand a chance as they were largely outnumbered and poorly armed, whereas the Federals were armed with repeaters. The Union soldiers crossed over a ditch while the rebels hurled primitive hand-grenades and fired their weapons.<ref>Trudeau, pp. 253-54</ref> Although the Union men had to assault under the fire of one 32-pounder gun and two 12-pounders inside the earthwork, the fort was captured. Confederate Brig. Gen. [[Robert C. Tyler]] was mortally wounded by a sharpshooter, becoming the last general officer to be killed in the Civil War.\n\nThe defense of West Point was doomed to fail, and had done so. With rebel prisoners, the fort, and bridge in his hands, La Grange moved out to rejoin Wilson. The battle had been won for the Union at a cost of 36 casualties both killed and wounded. The Confederates had lost 18 men killed, 28 wounded, and the remainder captured. With most of the dead southerners in the fort, one Yankee artilleryman said the dead Confederates wore \"an awful look.\"<ref>Trudeau, pp. 254</ref>\n\n===Columbus===\nIn a separate battle on Easter Sunday, April 16, Wilson was victorious in the [[Battle of Columbus, Georgia]], in which Upton's division clashed with Confederate forces at [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus]], capturing the city and its naval works and burning, then scuttling the incomplete [[ironclad]] [[Naval ram|ram]], [[CSS Muscogee|CSS ''Jackson'']]. This engagement is widely regarded as the \"Last Battle of the Civil War.\"<ref>[http://freepages.history.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~bellware/ Civil War Times, April 2003]</ref><ref>[http://freepages.history.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~bellware/paper.html \"The Last Battle of The Civil War,\" by Charles Swift.]</ref> On April 20, Wilson's men captured [[Macon, Georgia]], without resistance, and Wilson's Raid came to an end.  This was only six days before General [[Joseph E. Johnston]]'s surrender of all Confederate troops in the Carolinas, Georgia, and Florida to [[William Tecumseh Sherman]], in North Carolina.\n\n==Aftermath and capture of Jefferson Davis==\nWilson's Raid had been a spectacular success. His men captured five fortified cities, 288 cannons, and 6,820 prisoners, at a cost of 725 Union casualties. Forrest's casualties, from a much smaller force, numbered 1,200. The raid was done without the disastrous [[collateral damage]] that characterized [[Sherman's March to the Sea]] of the previous year. Residents accused Wilson's men of sacking Selma after the battle, but the damage there came from many sources including street combat that continued into the night, as well as 35,000 bales of cotton and the Central Commercial Warehouse fired by Confederates as the city fell.  Some Union soldiers and newly liberated former slaves did engage in plunder.  After the first night, Wilson re-established discipline.<ref>Jones, pp. 92-96</ref>\n\nUpon conclusion of the raid, and following the surrender of all of the Confederate forces east of the [[Chattahoochee River]] by Johnston to Sherman, the hostilities in the theater ended.  However, the pursuit of fleeing officials of the Confederate government commenced as Wilson's forces fanned out through the region.  Confederate President [[Jefferson Davis]] was captured on May 10, 1865, near [[Irwinville, Georgia]].<ref>Jones, pp. 170-176</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* [[David J. Eicher|Eicher, David J.]] ''The Longest Night: A Military History of the Civil War''. New York: Simon & Schuster, 2001. {{ISBN|0-684-84944-5}}.\n* [http://www.nps.gov/hps/abpp/battles/al007.htm National Park Service battle description for Selma]\n* Jones, James Pickett. ''Yankee Blitzkrieg, Wilson's Raid Through Alabama and Georgia''. Athens: University of Georgia Press, 1976. {{ISBN|978-0-8203-0370-3}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aotc.net/Selma.htm Army of the Cumberland website on Wilson's Raid]\n* [http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/face/Article.jsp?id=h-1375 Wilson's Raid article, Encyclopedia of Alabama]\n* [http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/bibb/wilsons-raid-to-macon Wilson's Raid to Macon] historical marker\n\n{{Coord|33.1596|-87.3423|region:US_type:event_scale:10000|display=title}}\n\n{{Alabama in the Civil War}}\n{{Georgia in the Civil War}}\n\n[[Category:Wilson's Raid| ]]\n[[Category:Selma, Alabama]]\n[[Category:History of Columbus, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Cavalry raids of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:1865 in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the American Civil War in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Military operations of the American Civil War in Alabama]]\n[[Category:1865 in the United States]]\n[[Category:March 1865 events]]\n[[Category:April 1865 events]]\n[[Category:1865 in Alabama]]\n", "name_user": "Djmaschek", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelma:Add link: 4th Cavalry Regiment (United States).", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilson%27s_Raid"}
{"title_page": "Melvyn Tan", "text_new": "'''Melvyn Tan''' ({{zh|s=\u9648\u4e07\u8363}}; born 13 October 1956) is a [[Singapore]]-born British [[classical music|classical]] [[pianist]], noted for his study of historical performance practice.<ref name=grove>{{cite web |first=Jessica |last=Duchen |url=http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/subscriber/article/grove/music/46065|title=\"Tan, Melvyn.\" |date=1 February 2010 |publisher=Grove Music Online / Oxford Music Online }}</ref>\n\nFrom a young age, he went to [[England]] to study, first at the [[Yehudi Menuhin School]] when he was twelve years old, later enrolling at the [[Royal College of Music]].<ref name=grove/>\n\nUpon returning to Singapore in 2005, he was fined for not having done [[National Service in Singapore]], although he was studying in London during the time he was required to serve,<ref>{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Mattison|date=6 December 2005 |url=http://www.playbillarts.com/news/article/3425.html |title=PlaybillArts: News: Pianist Melvyn Tan Cancels Return to Singapore Over Draft Controversy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091014121057/http://www.playbillarts.com/news/article/3425.html |archive-date=14 October 2009 |publisher=Playbill, Inc. }}</ref> he had already started a busy concert career, and he had already acquired [[British citizenship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/press_room/official_releases/nr/2006/jan/16jan06_nr.html|title=Ministerial Statement on National Service Defaulters by Minister for Defence Teo Chee Hean |date=16 January 2006 |publisher=Ministry of Defence }}</ref>\n\nDuring his development as a pianist, Tan developed a passion for the [[fortepiano]], which he has promoted throughout his career, and thereby changed other musicians' perceptions of this instrument. He has now returned mainly to the pianoforte and performs a wide-ranging repertoire from Bach to Messiaen.\n\nHe has lived in London since 1978, and continues to give concerts worldwide. In 2007, he performed at the [[Royal Academy of Arts]] for [[Jasper Conran]]'s London Fashion Week collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jasperconran.com/collections/womenswear/archive/a-w-2007,112,COL.html#nav=path_%252Fcollections%252Fwomenswear%252Farchive%252Fa-w-07-women%252C4%252CFV.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713090858/http://www.jasperconran.com/collections/womenswear/archive/a-w-2007%2C112%2CCOL.html|deadurl=y|title=Jasper Conran Autumn/Winter 2007 Collection Video|archivedate=13 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.melvyntan.com Melvyn Tan - Pianist]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150717030001/http://www.villamedici-giulini.it/corsi/melvyn-tan/melvyn-tan-eng.htm Masterclass with Melvyn Tan at Villa Medici Giulini, Briosco (MB) Italy]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tan, Melvyn}}\n[[Category:Singaporean classical pianists]]\n[[Category:British classical pianists]]\n[[Category:British fortepianists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:People educated at Yehudi Menuhin School]]\n[[Category:British people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Singaporean expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Singaporean people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical pianists]]\n", "text_old": "'''Melvyn Tan''' ({{zh|s=\u9648\u4e07\u8363}}; born 13 October 1956) is a [[Singapore]]-born British [[classical music|classical]] [[pianist]], noted for his study of historical performance practice.<ref name=grove>{{cite web |first=Jessica |last=Duchen |url=http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/subscriber/article/grove/music/46065|title=\"Tan, Melvyn.\" |date=1 February 2010 |publisher=Grove Music Online / Oxford Music Online }}</ref>\n\nFrom a young age, he went to [[England]] to study, first at the [[Yehudi Menuhin School]] when he was twelve years old, later enrolling at the [[Royal College of Music]].<ref name=grove/>\n\nUpon returning to Singapore in 2005, he was fined for not having done [[National Service in Singapore]], although he was studying in London during the time he was required to serve,<ref>{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Mattison|date=6 December 2005 |url=http://www.playbillarts.com/news/article/3425.html |title=PlaybillArts: News: Pianist Melvyn Tan Cancels Return to Singapore Over Draft Controversy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091014121057/http://www.playbillarts.com/news/article/3425.html |archive-date=14 October 2009 |publisher=Playbill, Inc. }}</ref> he had already started a busy concert career, and he had already acquired [[British citizenship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/press_room/official_releases/nr/2006/jan/16jan06_nr.html|title=Ministerial Statement on National Service Defaulters by Minister for Defence Teo Chee Hean |date=16 January 2006 |publisher=Ministry of Defence }}</ref>\n\nDuring his development as a pianist, Tan developed a passion for the [[fortepiano]], which he has promoted throughout his career, and thereby changed other musicians' perceptions of this instrument. He has now returned mainly to the pianoforte and performs a wide-ranging repertoire from Bach to Messiaen.\n\nHe has lived in London since 1978, and continues to give concerts worldwide. In 2007, he performed at the [[Royal Academy of Arts]] for [[Jasper Conran]]'s London Fashion Week collection.<ref>[https://www.jasperconran.com/collections/womenswear/archive/a-w-2007,112,COL.html#nav=path_%252Fcollections%252Fwomenswear%252Farchive%252Fa-w-07-women%252C4%252CFV.html Jasper Conran Autumn/Winter 2007 Collection Video] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713090858/http://www.jasperconran.com/collections/womenswear/archive/a-w-2007%2C112%2CCOL.html |date=13 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.melvyntan.com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150717030001/http://www.villamedici-giulini.it/corsi/melvyn-tan/melvyn-tan-eng.htm Masterclass with Melvyn Tan at Villa Medici Giulini, Briosco (MB) Italy]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tan, Melvyn}}\n[[Category:Singaporean classical pianists]]\n[[Category:British classical pianists]]\n[[Category:British fortepianists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:People educated at Yehudi Menuhin School]]\n[[Category:British people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Singaporean expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Singaporean people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical pianists]]\n", "name_user": "Ukexpat", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 1 bare reference(s) with reFill 2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melvyn_Tan"}
{"title_page": "Methocarbamol", "text_new": "{{Drugbox\n| Verifiedfields     = changed\n| Watchedfields      = changed\n| verifiedrevid      = 457287029\n| drug_name          = \n| type               = \n| IUPAC_name         = (''RS'')-2-hydroxy-3-(2-methoxyphenoxy)propyl carbamate\n| image              = Methocarbamol.svg\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| tradename          = Robaxin, Marbaxin, others\n| Drugs.com          = {{drugs.com|monograph|methocarbamol}}\n| MedlinePlus        = a682579\n| licence_EU         = \n| licence_US         = \n| pregnancy_AU       = B2\n| pregnancy_US       = C\n| pregnancy_category = \n| legal_CA           = OTC\n| legal_US           = Rx-only\n| legal_status       = \n| routes_of_administration = By mouth, intravenous\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability    = \n| protein_bound      = \n| metabolism         = Liver\n| elimination_half-life = 1.14\u20131.24 hours<ref name = \"halflife\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Sica DA, Comstock TJ, Davis J, Manning L, Powell R, Melikian A, Wright G | title = Pharmacokinetics and protein binding of methocarbamol in renal insufficiency and normals | journal = [[European Journal of Clinical Pharmacology]] | year = 1990 | volume = 39 | issue = 2 | pages = 193\u20134 | pmid = 2253675 | doi = 10.1007/BF00280060}}</ref>\n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| IUPHAR_ligand      = 6829\n| CAS_number_Ref     = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CAS_number         = 532-03-6\n| ATC_prefix         = M03\n| ATC_suffix         = BA03\n| ATC_supplemental   = \n| PubChem            = 4107\n| DrugBank_Ref       = {{drugbankcite|correct|drugbank}}\n| DrugBank           = DB00423\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref   = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID       = 3964\n| UNII_Ref           = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII               = 125OD7737X\n| KEGG_Ref           = {{keggcite|correct|kegg}}\n| KEGG               = D00402\n| ChEBI_Ref          = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEBI              = 6832\n| ChEMBL_Ref         = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL             = 1201117\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C = 11| H = 15| N = 1| O = 5\n| molecular_weight   = 241.241 g/mol\n| smiles             = O=C(OCC(O)COc1ccccc1OC)N\n| StdInChI_Ref       = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI           = 1S/C11H15NO5/c1-15-9-4-2-3-5-10(9)16-6-8(13)7-17-11(12)14/h2-5,8,13H,6-7H2,1H3,(H2,12,14)\n| StdInChIKey_Ref    = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey        = GNXFOGHNGIVQEH-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n<!-- Definition and medical uses -->\n'''Methocarbamol''', sold under the brand name '''Robaxin''' among others, is a medication used for short-term [[musculoskeletal]] pain.<ref name=AHFS2019/><ref name=BNF76/> It may be used together with rest and [[pain medication]].<ref name=AHFS2019/> It is less preferred in [[low back pain]].<ref name=AHFS2019/> It has limited use for [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and [[cerebral palsy]].<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" /><ref name=Ric2012>{{Cite journal|last=Richards|first=Bethan L.|last2=Whittle|first2=Samuel L.|last3=Buchbinder|first3=Rachelle|date=2012-01-18|title=Muscle relaxants for pain management in rheumatoid arthritis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22258993|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=1|pages=CD008922|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD008922.pub2|issn=1469-493X|pmid=22258993}}</ref> Effects generally begin within half an hour.<ref name=AHFS2019/> It is taken by mouth or [[intravenous|injection into a vein]].<ref name=AHFS2019/>\n\n<!-- Side effects and mechanism -->\nCommon side effect include headaches, sleepiness, dizziness.<ref name=AHFS2019/><ref name=\"Liver2017\">{{Citation|title=Methocarbamol|date=2012|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK548286/|work=LiverTox: Clinical and Research Information on Drug-Induced Liver Injury|publisher=National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases|pmid=31643609|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Serious side effects may include [[anaphylaxis]], liver problems, confusion, and [[seizure]]s.<ref name=BNF76/> Use is not recommended in [[pregnancy]] and [[breastfeeding]].<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" /> Use by the elderly is considered high risk.<ref name=AHFS2019/> Methocarbamol is a centrally acting [[muscle relaxant]].<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" /> How it works is unclear, but it does not appear to affect muscles directly.<ref name=AHFS2019/>\n\n<!-- History and culture -->\nMethocarbamol was approved for medical use in the United States in 1957.<ref name=AHFS2019>{{cite web |title=Methocarbamol Monograph for Professionals |url=https://www.drugs.com/monograph/methocarbamol.html |website=Drugs.com |publisher=American Society of Health-System Pharmacists |language=en}}</ref> It is available as a [[generic medication]].<ref name=AHFS2019/><ref name=BNF76/> In 2016, it was the 187th most prescribed medication in the United States with more than 3 million prescriptions.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Top 300 of 2019 |url=https://clincalc.com/DrugStats/Top300Drugs.aspx |website=clincalc.com |accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Medical use ==\nMethocarbamol is a muscle relaxant used to treat acute, painful musculoskeletal spasms in a variety of musculoskeletal conditions.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Chou|first=Roger|last2=Peterson|first2=Kim|last3=Helfand|first3=Mark|date=August 2004|title=Comparative efficacy and safety of skeletal muscle relaxants for spasticity and musculoskeletal conditions: a systematic review|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15276195|journal=Journal of Pain and Symptom Management|volume=28|issue=2|pages=140\u2013175|doi=10.1016/j.jpainsymman.2004.05.002|issn=0885-3924|pmid=15276195|via=}}</ref> Several trials have indicated that methocarbamol is an efficient and well-tolerated option in acute [[Low back pain|lower back pain]] and the associated restrictions of mobility.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tisdale|first=S. A.|last2=Ervin|first2=D. K.|date=June 1975|title=A controlled study of methocarbamol (Robaxin) in acute painful musculoskeletal conditions|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/808374|journal=Current Therapeutic Research, Clinical and Experimental|volume=17|issue=6|pages=525\u2013530|issn=0011-393X|pmid=808374|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Emrich|first=Oliver M. D.|last2=Milachowski|first2=Klaus A.|last3=Strohmeier|first3=Martin|date=July 2015|title=[Methocarbamol in acute low back pain. A randomized double-blind controlled study]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26168743|journal=MMW Fortschritte der Medizin|volume=157 Suppl 5|pages=9\u201316|doi=10.1007/s15006-015-3307-x|issn=1438-3276|pmid=26168743|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chou|first=Roger|last2=Deyo|first2=Richard|last3=Friedly|first3=Janna|last4=Skelly|first4=Andrea|last5=Weimer|first5=Melissa|last6=Fu|first6=Rochelle|last7=Dana|first7=Tracy|last8=Kraegel|first8=Paul|last9=Griffin|first9=Jessica|last10=Grusing|first10=Sara|date=2017-04-04|title=Systemic Pharmacologic Therapies for Low Back Pain: A Systematic Review for an American College of Physicians Clinical Practice Guideline|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28192790|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|volume=166|issue=7|pages=480\u2013492|doi=10.7326/M16-2458|issn=1539-3704|pmid=28192790}}</ref> However, there is limited and inconsistent published research on the medication's efficacy and safety in treating musculoskeletal conditions, primarily neck and back pain.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nMethocarbamol injection may have a beneficial effect in the control of the neuromuscular spasms of [[tetanus]].<ref name=\":0\">Hikma Pharmaceuticals. Robaxin Injectable (methocarbamol injection, USP) [package insert]. U.S. Food and Drug Administration Website. https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/label/2004/11790slr046_robaxin_lbl.pdf. Revised November 2003, Accessed April 19, 2020.</ref> It does not, however, replace the current treatment regimen.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIt is not useful in chronic neurological disorders, such as [[cerebral palsy]] or other [[Dyskinesia|dyskinesias]].<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" />\n\nCurrently, there is some suggestion that muscle relaxants may improve the symptoms of [[rheumatoid arthritis]], however, there is insufficient data to prove its effectiveness as well as answer concerns regarding optimal dosing, choice of muscle relaxant, adverse effects, and functional status.<ref name=Ric2012/>\n\n=== Comparison to similar agents ===\nThe clinical effectiveness of methocarbamol compared to other muscle relaxants is not well-known.<ref name=\":3\" /> One trial of methocarbamol versus [[cyclobenzaprine]], a well-studied muscle relaxant, in those with localized muscle spasm found there was no significant differences in their effects on improved muscle spasm, limitation of motion, or limitation of daily activities.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Contraindications ==\nThere are few contraindications to methocarbamol. They include:\n\n* Hypersensitivity to methocarbamol or to any of the injection components<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Suspected kidney failure or renal pathology due to large content of [[Polyethylene glycol|polyethylene glycol 300]] that can increase pre-existing [[acidosis]] and [[Uremia|urea retention]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Side effects==\nMethocarbamol is a centrally acting skeletal muscle relaxant that has significant adverse effects, especially on the central nervous system.<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" />\n\nPotential side effects of methocarbamol include:\n\n* Most commonly drowsiness, blurred vision, headache, nausea, and skin rash.<ref name=Liver2017 />\n*Clumsiness ([[ataxia]]), upset stomach, flushing, mood changes, trouble urinating, itchiness, and fever.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://medlineplus.gov/druginfo/meds/a682579.html|title=Methocarbamol: MedlinePlus Drug Information|website=medlineplus.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" />\n* Both [[tachycardia]] (fast heart rate) and [[bradycardia]] (slow heart rate) have been reported.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.drugs.com/sfx/methocarbamol-side-effects.html|title=Methocarbamol Side Effects: Common, Severe, Long Term|website=Drugs.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n*May cause respiratory depression if combined when combined with [[Benzodiazepine|benzodiazepines]], [[Barbiturate|barbiturates]], [[codeine]], or other muscle relaxants<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=See|first=Sharon|last2=Ginzburg|first2=Regina|date=2008-08-01|title=Choosing a skeletal muscle relaxant|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18711953|journal=American Family Physician|volume=78|issue=3|pages=365\u2013370|issn=0002-838X|pmid=18711953}}</ref>\n* May cause urine to turn black, blue or green.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nWhile the product label states that methocarbamol can cause [[jaundice]], there is minimal evidence to suggest that methocarbamol causes liver damage.<ref name=Liver2017 /> During clinical trials of methocarbamol, there were no laboratory measurements of liver damage indicators, such as serum [[aminotransferase]] ([[Aspartate transaminase|AST]]/[[Alanine transaminase|ALT]]) levels, to confirm [[hepatotoxicity]].<ref name=Liver2017 /> Although unlikely, it is impossible to rule out that methocarbamol may cause mild liver injury with use.<ref name=Liver2017 />\n\n=== Elderly ===\nSkeletal muscle relaxants are associated with an increased risk of injury among older adults.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Spence|first=Michele M.|last2=Shin|first2=Patrick J.|last3=Lee|first3=Eric A.|last4=Gibbs|first4=Nancy E.|date=July 2013|title=Risk of injury associated with skeletal muscle relaxant use in older adults|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23821610|journal=The Annals of Pharmacotherapy|volume=47|issue=7-8|pages=993\u2013998|doi=10.1345/aph.1R735|issn=1542-6270|pmid=23821610|via=}}</ref> Methocarbamol appeared to be less sedating than other muscle relaxants, most notably [[cyclobenzaprine]], but had similar increased risk of injury.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> The medication was listed on the 2012 [[Beers criteria|Beers Criteria]] for Potentially Inappropriate Medication Use in Older Adults and is considered to be a high-risk medication for the elderly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dcri.org/beers-criteria-medication-list/|title=Beers Criteria Medication List|website=DCRI|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Pregnancy ===\nMethocarbamol is currently labeled by the FDA as a [[pregnancy category]] C medication.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[Teratology|teratogenic]] effects of the medication are not known and should be given to pregnant women only when clearly indicated.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Overdose ===\nOverdose is used frequently in conjunction with CNS depressants such as [[alcohol]] or [[Benzodiazepine|benzodiazepines]] and will have symptoms of nausea, drowsiness, blurred vision, [[hypotension]], seizures, and coma.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Abuse===\nUnlike other carbamates such as [[meprobamate]] and its prodrug [[carisoprodol]], methocarbamol has greatly reduced abuse potential.<ref name=\"PubMed\" />  Studies comparing it to the benzodiazepine [[lorazepam]] and the antihistamine [[diphenhydramine]], along with placebo, find that methocarbamol produces increased \"liking\" responses and some sedative-like effects; however, at higher doses [[dysphoria]] is reported.<ref name=\"PubMed\" />  It is considered to have an abuse profile similar to, but weaker than, [[lorazepam]].<ref name = \"PubMed\">{{cite journal | title = Subjective and behavioral effects of diphenhydramine, lorazepam and methocarbamol: evaluation of abuse liability | journal = Journal of Pharmacology and Experimental Therapeutics | pmid=1501118 | volume=262 | issue = 2 | pages=707\u201320 | vauthors=Preston KL, Wolf B, Guarino JJ, Griffiths RR| year = 1992 }}</ref>\n\n== Interactions ==\nMethocarbamol may inhibit the effects of [[Pyridostigmine|pyridostigmine bromide]].<ref name=\"FDA2020Label\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/label/2004/11790slr046_robaxin_lbl.pdf|title=Drugs@FDA: FDA-Approved Drugs|last=|first=|date=|website=www.accessdata.fda.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Therefore, methocarbamol should be used with caution in those with [[myasthenia gravis]] taking [[Cholinesterase inhibitor|anticholinesterase]] medications.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMethocarbamol may disrupt certain screening tests as it can cause color interference in laboratory tests for [[5-Hydroxyindoleacetic acid|5-hydroxy-indoleacetic acid (5-HIAA)]] and in urinary testing for [[Vanillylmandelic acid|vanillylmandelic acid (VMA)]] using the Gitlow method.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Pharmacology==\n\n=== Mechanism of action ===\nThe mechanism of action of methocarbamol has not currently been established.<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" /> Its effect is thought to be localized to the central nervous system rather than a direct effect on skeletal muscles.<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" /> It has no effect on the motor end plate or the peripheral nerve fiber.<ref name=\":0\" /> The efficacy of the medication is likely related to its sedative effect.<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" />\n\n=== Pharmacokinetics ===\nIn healthy individuals, the plasma clearance of methocarbamol ranges between 0.20 and 0.80 L/h/kg.<ref name=\":0\" /> The mean plasma elimination half-life ranges between 1 and 2 hours, and the plasma protein binding ranges between 46% and 50%.<ref name=\":0\" /> The elimination half-life was longer in the elderly, those with [[kidney]] problems, and those with [[liver]] problems.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Metabolism ===\nMethocarbamol is the [[carbamate]] derivative of [[guaifenesin]], but does not produce guaifenesin as a [[metabolite]], because the carbamate bond is not hydrolyzed metabolically;<ref name=\"Liver2017\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> it's metabolism is by Phase I ring hydroxylation and ''O''-demethylation, followed by Phase II conjugation.<ref name=\":0\" /> All the major metabolites are unhydrolyzed carbamates.<ref>Methocarbamol. In: ''DRUGDEX System'' [intranet database]. Greenwood Village, Colorado: Thomson Healthcare; c1974\u20132009 [cited 2009 Feb 10].</ref><ref name=\"metabolismBruce1971\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Bruce RB, Turnbull LB, Newman JH | title = Metabolism of methocarbamol in the rat, dog, and human | journal = J Pharm Sci | date = Jan 1971 | volume = 60 | issue = 1 | pages = 104\u2013106 | pmid = 5548215 | doi = 10.1002/jps.2600600120}}</ref> Small amounts of unchanged methocarbamol are also excreted in the urine.<ref name=FDA2020Label />\n\n==Society and culture==\nMethocarbamol was approved as a muscle relaxant for acute, painful musculoskeletal conditions in the United States in 1957.<ref name=Liver2017 /> Muscle relaxants are widely used to treat low back pain, one of the most frequent health problems in industrialized countries.<ref name=\":4\" /> Currently, there are more than 3 million prescriptions filled yearly.<ref name=Liver2017 /> Methocarbamol and [[orphenadrine]], are each used in more than 250,000 U.S. emergency department visits for lower back pain each year.<ref name=\":2\" /> In the United States, low back pain is the fifth most common reason for all physician visits and the second most common symptomatic reason.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chou|first=Roger|last2=Huffman|first2=Laurie Hoyt|date=2007-10-02|title=Medications for Acute and Chronic Low Back Pain: A Review of the Evidence for an American Pain Society/American College of Physicians Clinical Practice Guideline|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.7326/0003-4819-147-7-200710020-00008|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|volume=147|issue=7|pages=505|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-147-7-200710020-00008|issn=0003-4819}}</ref> In 80% of primary care visits for low back pain, at least one medication was prescribed at the initial office visit and more than one third were prescribed two or more medications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cherkin|first=D. C.|last2=Wheeler|first2=K. J.|last3=Barlow|first3=W.|last4=Deyo|first4=R. A.|date=1998-03-01|title=Medication use for low back pain in primary care|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9530793|journal=Spine|volume=23|issue=5|pages=607\u2013614|doi=10.1097/00007632-199803010-00015|issn=0362-2436|pmid=9530793}}</ref> The most commonly prescribed drugs for low back pain included skeletal muscle relaxants.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Luo|first=Xuemei|last2=Pietrobon|first2=Ricardo|last3=Curtis|first3=Lesley H.|last4=Hey|first4=Lloyd A.|date=2004-12-01|title=Prescription of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs and muscle relaxants for back pain in the United States|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15564901|journal=Spine|volume=29|issue=23|pages=E531\u2013537|doi=10.1097/01.brs.0000146453.76528.7c|issn=1528-1159|pmid=15564901}}</ref> [[Cyclobenzaprine]] and methocarbamol are on the U.S. [[Medicare]] formulary, which may account for the higher use of these products.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n===Economics===\nThe generic formulation of the medication is relatively inexpensive costing less than the alternative [[metaxalone]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Robbins |first1=Lawrence D. |title=Management of Headache and Headache Medications |date=2013 |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |isbn=978-1-4612-2124-1 |page=PT147 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Management_of_Headache_and_Headache_Medi/Bmh3BQAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Methocarbamol+inexpensive&pg=PT147 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Fine |first1=Perry G. |title=The Hospice Companion: Best Practices for Interdisciplinary Care of Advanced Illness |date=2016 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-045692-4 |page=PT146 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Hospice_Companion/I7NjDQAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Methocarbamol+cost&pg=PT146 |language=en}}</ref> In the UK costs the [[NHS]] pay about \u00a313 for 100 tablets of 750 mg of methocarbamol as of 2019.<ref name=BNF76>{{cite book|title=British national formulary : BNF 76|date=2018|publisher=Pharmaceutical Press|isbn=9780857113382|pages=1093|edition=76}}</ref> In the US the [[NADAC|wholesale cost]] of this quantity is about US$10 as of 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=NADAC as of 2020-04-15 {{!}} Data.Medicaid.gov |url=https://data.medicaid.gov/Drug-Pricing-and-Payment/NADAC-as-of-2020-04-15/rj2z-7f86 |website=Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\n[[File:Methocarbamol 750 MG Oral Tablet.jpg|thumb|Generic methocarbamol 750mg tablet.]]\nMethocarbamol without other ingredients is sold under the brand name Robaxin in the U.K., U.S. and Canada; it is marketed as Lumirelax in France, Ortoton in Germany and many other names worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Methocarbamol|url=https://www.drugs.com/international/methocarbamol.html|website=Drugs.com|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref> In combination with other active ingredients it is sold under other names: with [[acetaminophen]] (Paracetamol), under trade names Robaxacet and Tylenol Body Pain Night; with [[ibuprofen]] as Robax Platinum; with [[acetylsalicylic acid]] as Robaxisal in the U.S. and Canada.<ref name=\"ESI\">{{cite web | title = New Drugs and Indications Reviewed at the May 2003 DEC Meeting | publisher = [[Express Scripts Incorporated|ESI Canada]] | url = http://www.esi-canada.com/aboutus/news/health_newsflashes/volume5_issue9_newdrugsmay2003.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate = 2008-11-14 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110710201457/http://www.esi-canada.com/aboutus/news/health_newsflashes/volume5_issue9_newdrugsmay2003.pdf | archivedate = 2011-07-10 }}</ref><ref name=\"Tylenol\">{{cite web | title = Tylenol Body Pain Night Overview and Dosage | publisher = [[Johnson & Johnson|Tylenol Canada]] | url = http://www.tylenol.ca/adult-pain-relief/tylenol-body-pain-night | format = website | accessdate = 2012-04-23 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120331074351/http://www.tylenol.ca/adult-pain-relief/tylenol-body-pain-night | archivedate = 2012-03-31 }}</ref> However, in Spain the tradename Robaxisal is used for the paracetamol combination instead of Robaxacet. These combinations are also available from independent manufacturers under generic names.\n\n== Research ==\nAlthough [[Opioid|opioids]] are a typically first line in treatment of severe pain, research suggests that methocarbamol may improve recovery and decrease hospital length of stay in those with muscles spasms associated with [[Rib fracture|rib fractures]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Patanwala|first=Asad E.|last2=Aljuhani|first2=Ohoud|last3=Kopp|first3=Brian J.|last4=Erstad|first4=Brian L.|date=October 2017|title=Methocarbamol use is associated with decreased hospital length of stay in trauma patients with closed rib fractures|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.amjsurg.2017.01.003|journal=The American Journal of Surgery|volume=214|issue=4|pages=738\u2013742|doi=10.1016/j.amjsurg.2017.01.003|issn=0002-9610|via=}}</ref> However, methocarbamol was less useful in the treatment of acute traumatic pain in general.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Aljuhani|first=Ohoud|last2=Kopp|first2=Brian J.|last3=Patanwala|first3=Asad E.|date=2017|title=Effect of Methocarbamol on Acute Pain After Traumatic Injury|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1097/mjt.0000000000000364|journal=American Journal of Therapeutics|volume=24|issue=2|pages=e202\u2013e206|doi=10.1097/mjt.0000000000000364|issn=1075-2765}}</ref>\n\nMethocarbamol has also been suggested to be a safe and well-tolerated medication in the treatment of muscle cramps in those with [[Cirrhosis|liver cirrhosis]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abd-Elsalam|first=Sherief|last2=Arafa|first2=Mona|last3=Elkadeem|first3=Mahmoud|last4=Elfert|first4=Asem|last5=Soliman|first5=Shaimaa|last6=Elkhalawany|first6=Walaa|last7=Badawi|first7=Rehab|date=April 2019|title=Randomized-controlled trial of methocarbamol as a novel treatment for muscle cramps in cirrhotic patients|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30444744|journal=European Journal of Gastroenterology & Hepatology|volume=31|issue=4|pages=499\u2013502|doi=10.1097/MEG.0000000000001310|issn=1473-5687|pmid=30444744|via=}}</ref>\n\nA randomized, double-blind, placebo controlled trial of oral [[naproxen]] with or without methocarbamol or [[orphenadrine]] for acute lower back pain showed the combination of either muscle relaxant with naproxen did not improve functional outcomes compared to naproxen combined placebo.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Friedman|first=Benjamin W.|last2=Cisewski|first2=David|last3=Irizarry|first3=Eddie|last4=Davitt|first4=Michelle|last5=Solorzano|first5=Clemencia|last6=Nassery|first6=Adam|last7=Pearlman|first7=Scott|last8=White|first8=Deborah|last9=Gallagher|first9=E. John|date=March 2018|title=A Randomized, Double-Blind, Placebo-Controlled Trial of Naproxen With or Without Orphenadrine or Methocarbamol for Acute Low Back Pain|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29089169|journal=Annals of Emergency Medicine|volume=71|issue=3|pages=348\u2013356.e5|doi=10.1016/j.annemergmed.2017.09.031|issn=1097-6760|pmc=5820149|pmid=29089169|via=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chlorphenesin]]\n* [[Mephenesin]]\n* [[Mephenoxalone]]\n* [[Metaxalone]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Muscle relaxants}}\n\n[[Category:RTT]]\n[[Category:Muscle relaxants]]\n[[Category:Veterinary drugs]]\n[[Category:Carbamates]]\n[[Category:Catechol ethers]]\n[[Category:Secondary alcohols]]\n[[Category:Drugs with unknown mechanisms of action]]\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| Verifiedfields     = changed\n| Watchedfields      = changed\n| verifiedrevid      = 457287029\n| drug_name          = \n| type               = \n| IUPAC_name         = (''RS'')-2-hydroxy-3-(2-methoxyphenoxy)propyl carbamate\n| image              = Methocarbamol.svg\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| tradename          = Robaxin, Marbaxin, others\n| Drugs.com          = {{drugs.com|monograph|methocarbamol}}\n| MedlinePlus        = a682579\n| licence_EU         = \n| licence_US         = \n| pregnancy_AU       = B2\n| pregnancy_US       = C\n| pregnancy_category = \n| legal_CA           = OTC\n| legal_US           = Rx-only\n| legal_status       = \n| routes_of_administration = By mouth, intravenous\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability    = \n| protein_bound      = \n| metabolism         = Liver\n| elimination_half-life = 1.14\u20131.24 hours<ref name = \"halflife\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Sica DA, Comstock TJ, Davis J, Manning L, Powell R, Melikian A, Wright G | title = Pharmacokinetics and protein binding of methocarbamol in renal insufficiency and normals | journal = [[European Journal of Clinical Pharmacology]] | year = 1990 | volume = 39 | issue = 2 | pages = 193\u20134 | pmid = 2253675 | doi = 10.1007/BF00280060}}</ref>\n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| IUPHAR_ligand      = 6829\n| CAS_number_Ref     = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CAS_number         = 532-03-6\n| ATC_prefix         = M03\n| ATC_suffix         = BA03\n| ATC_supplemental   = \n| PubChem            = 4107\n| DrugBank_Ref       = {{drugbankcite|correct|drugbank}}\n| DrugBank           = DB00423\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref   = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID       = 3964\n| UNII_Ref           = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII               = 125OD7737X\n| KEGG_Ref           = {{keggcite|correct|kegg}}\n| KEGG               = D00402\n| ChEBI_Ref          = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEBI              = 6832\n| ChEMBL_Ref         = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL             = 1201117\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C = 11| H = 15| N = 1| O = 5\n| molecular_weight   = 241.241 g/mol\n| smiles             = O=C(OCC(O)COc1ccccc1OC)N\n| StdInChI_Ref       = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI           = 1S/C11H15NO5/c1-15-9-4-2-3-5-10(9)16-6-8(13)7-17-11(12)14/h2-5,8,13H,6-7H2,1H3,(H2,12,14)\n| StdInChIKey_Ref    = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey        = GNXFOGHNGIVQEH-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n<!-- Definition and medical uses -->\n'''Methocarbamol''', sold under the brand name '''Robaxin''' among others, is a medication used for short-term [[musculoskeletal]] pain.<ref name=AHFS2019/><ref name=BNF76/> It may be used together with rest and [[pain medication]].<ref name=AHFS2019/> It is less preferred in [[low back pain]].<ref name=AHFS2019/> It has limited use for [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and [[cerebral palsy]].<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" /><ref name=Ric2012>{{Cite journal|last=Richards|first=Bethan L.|last2=Whittle|first2=Samuel L.|last3=Buchbinder|first3=Rachelle|date=2012-01-18|title=Muscle relaxants for pain management in rheumatoid arthritis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22258993|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=1|pages=CD008922|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD008922.pub2|issn=1469-493X|pmid=22258993}}</ref> Effects generally begin within half an hour.<ref name=AHFS2019/> It is taken by mouth or [[intravenous|injection into a vein]].<ref name=AHFS2019/>\n\n<!-- Side effects and mechanism -->\nCommon side effect include headaches, sleepiness, dizziness.<ref name=AHFS2019/><ref name=\"Liver2017\">{{Citation|title=Methocarbamol|date=2012|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK548286/|work=LiverTox: Clinical and Research Information on Drug-Induced Liver Injury|publisher=National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases|pmid=31643609|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Serious side effects may include [[anaphylaxis]], liver problems, confusion, and [[seizure]]s.<ref name=BNF76/> Use is not recommended in [[pregnancy]] and [[breastfeeding]].<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" /> Use by the elderly is considered high risk.<ref name=AHFS2019/> Methocarbamol is a centrally acting [[muscle relaxant]].<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" /> How it works is unclear, but it does not appear to affect muscles directly.<ref name=AHFS2019/>\n\n<!-- History and culture -->\nMethocarbamol was approved for medical use in the United States in 1957.<ref name=AHFS2019>{{cite web |title=Methocarbamol Monograph for Professionals |url=https://www.drugs.com/monograph/methocarbamol.html |website=Drugs.com |publisher=American Society of Health-System Pharmacists |language=en}}</ref> It is available as a [[generic medication]].<ref name=AHFS2019/><ref name=BNF76/> In 2016, it was the 187th most prescribed medication in the United States with more than 3 million prescriptions.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Top 300 of 2019 |url=https://clincalc.com/DrugStats/Top300Drugs.aspx |website=clincalc.com |accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Medical use ==\nMethocarbamol is a muscle relaxant used to treat acute, painful musculoskeletal spasms in a variety of musculoskeletal conditions.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Chou|first=Roger|last2=Peterson|first2=Kim|last3=Helfand|first3=Mark|date=August 2004|title=Comparative efficacy and safety of skeletal muscle relaxants for spasticity and musculoskeletal conditions: a systematic review|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15276195|journal=Journal of Pain and Symptom Management|volume=28|issue=2|pages=140\u2013175|doi=10.1016/j.jpainsymman.2004.05.002|issn=0885-3924|pmid=15276195|via=}}</ref> Several trials have indicated that methocarbamol is an efficient and well-tolerated option in acute [[Low back pain|lower back pain]] and the associated restrictions of mobility.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tisdale|first=S. A.|last2=Ervin|first2=D. K.|date=June 1975|title=A controlled study of methocarbamol (Robaxin) in acute painful musculoskeletal conditions|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/808374|journal=Current Therapeutic Research, Clinical and Experimental|volume=17|issue=6|pages=525\u2013530|issn=0011-393X|pmid=808374|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Emrich|first=Oliver M. D.|last2=Milachowski|first2=Klaus A.|last3=Strohmeier|first3=Martin|date=July 2015|title=[Methocarbamol in acute low back pain. A randomized double-blind controlled study]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26168743|journal=MMW Fortschritte der Medizin|volume=157 Suppl 5|pages=9\u201316|doi=10.1007/s15006-015-3307-x|issn=1438-3276|pmid=26168743|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chou|first=Roger|last2=Deyo|first2=Richard|last3=Friedly|first3=Janna|last4=Skelly|first4=Andrea|last5=Weimer|first5=Melissa|last6=Fu|first6=Rochelle|last7=Dana|first7=Tracy|last8=Kraegel|first8=Paul|last9=Griffin|first9=Jessica|last10=Grusing|first10=Sara|date=2017-04-04|title=Systemic Pharmacologic Therapies for Low Back Pain: A Systematic Review for an American College of Physicians Clinical Practice Guideline|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28192790|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|volume=166|issue=7|pages=480\u2013492|doi=10.7326/M16-2458|issn=1539-3704|pmid=28192790}}</ref> However, there is limited and inconsistent published research on the medication's efficacy and safety in treating musculoskeletal conditions, primarily neck and back pain.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nMethocarbamol injection may have a beneficial effect in the control of the neuromuscular spasms of [[tetanus]].<ref name=\"FDA2020Label\" /> It does not, however, replace the current treatment regimen.<ref name=\"FDA2020Label\" />\n\nIt is not useful in chronic neurological disorders, such as [[cerebral palsy]] or other [[Dyskinesia|dyskinesias]].<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" />\n\nCurrently, there is some suggestion that muscle relaxants may improve the symptoms of [[rheumatoid arthritis]], however, there is insufficient data to prove its effectiveness as well as answer concerns regarding optimal dosing, choice of muscle relaxant, adverse effects, and functional status.<ref name=Ric2012/>\n\n=== Comparison to similar agents ===\nThe clinical effectiveness of methocarbamol compared to other muscle relaxants is not well-known.<ref name=\":3\" /> One trial of methocarbamol versus [[cyclobenzaprine]], a well-studied muscle relaxant, in those with localized muscle spasm found there was no significant differences in their effects on improved muscle spasm, limitation of motion, or limitation of daily activities.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Contraindications ==\nThere are few contraindications to methocarbamol. They include:\n\n* Hypersensitivity to methocarbamol or to any of the injection components<ref name=\"FDA2020Label\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/label/2004/11790slr046_robaxin_lbl.pdf|title=Drugs@FDA: FDA-Approved Drugs|last=|first=|date=|website=www.accessdata.fda.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n* Suspected kidney failure or renal pathology due to large content of [[Polyethylene glycol|polyethylene glycol 300]] that can increase pre-existing [[acidosis]] and [[Uremia|urea retention]]<ref name=\"FDA2020Label\" />\n\n==Side effects==\nMethocarbamol is a centrally acting skeletal muscle relaxant that has significant adverse effects, especially on the central nervous system.<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" />\n\nPotential side effects of methocarbamol include:\n\n* Most commonly drowsiness, blurred vision, headache, nausea, and skin rash.<ref name=Liver2017 />\n*Clumsiness ([[ataxia]]), upset stomach, flushing, mood changes, trouble urinating, itchiness, and fever.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://medlineplus.gov/druginfo/meds/a682579.html|title=Methocarbamol: MedlinePlus Drug Information|website=medlineplus.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" />\n* Both [[tachycardia]] (fast heart rate) and [[bradycardia]] (slow heart rate) have been reported.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.drugs.com/sfx/methocarbamol-side-effects.html|title=Methocarbamol Side Effects: Common, Severe, Long Term|website=Drugs.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n*May cause respiratory depression if combined when combined with [[Benzodiazepine|benzodiazepines]], [[Barbiturate|barbiturates]], [[codeine]], or other muscle relaxants<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=See|first=Sharon|last2=Ginzburg|first2=Regina|date=2008-08-01|title=Choosing a skeletal muscle relaxant|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18711953|journal=American Family Physician|volume=78|issue=3|pages=365\u2013370|issn=0002-838X|pmid=18711953}}</ref>\n* May cause urine to turn black, blue or green.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nWhile the product label states that methocarbamol can cause [[jaundice]], there is minimal evidence to suggest that methocarbamol causes liver damage.<ref name=Liver2017 /> During clinical trials of methocarbamol, there were no laboratory measurements of liver damage indicators, such as serum [[aminotransferase]] ([[Aspartate transaminase|AST]]/[[Alanine transaminase|ALT]]) levels, to confirm [[hepatotoxicity]].<ref name=Liver2017 /> Although unlikely, it is impossible to rule out that methocarbamol may cause mild liver injury with use.<ref name=Liver2017 />\n\n=== Elderly ===\nSkeletal muscle relaxants are associated with an increased risk of injury among older adults.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Spence|first=Michele M.|last2=Shin|first2=Patrick J.|last3=Lee|first3=Eric A.|last4=Gibbs|first4=Nancy E.|date=July 2013|title=Risk of injury associated with skeletal muscle relaxant use in older adults|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23821610|journal=The Annals of Pharmacotherapy|volume=47|issue=7-8|pages=993\u2013998|doi=10.1345/aph.1R735|issn=1542-6270|pmid=23821610|via=}}</ref> Methocarbamol appeared to be less sedating than other muscle relaxants, most notably [[cyclobenzaprine]], but had similar increased risk of injury.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> The medication was listed on the 2012 [[Beers criteria|Beers Criteria]] for Potentially Inappropriate Medication Use in Older Adults and is considered to be a high-risk medication for the elderly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dcri.org/beers-criteria-medication-list/|title=Beers Criteria Medication List|website=DCRI|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Pregnancy ===\nMethocarbamol is currently labeled by the FDA as a [[pregnancy category]] C medication.<ref name=FDA2020Label /> The [[Teratology|teratogenic]] effects of the medication are not known and should be given to pregnant women only when clearly indicated.<ref name=FDA2020Label />\n\n=== Overdose ===\nOverdose is used frequently in conjunction with CNS depressants such as [[alcohol]] or [[Benzodiazepine|benzodiazepines]] and will have symptoms of nausea, drowsiness, blurred vision, [[hypotension]], seizures, and coma.<ref name=FDA2020Label />\n\n=== Abuse===\nUnlike other carbamates such as [[meprobamate]] and its prodrug [[carisoprodol]], methocarbamol has greatly reduced abuse potential.<ref name=\"PubMed\" />  Studies comparing it to the benzodiazepine [[lorazepam]] and the antihistamine [[diphenhydramine]], along with placebo, find that methocarbamol produces increased \"liking\" responses and some sedative-like effects; however, at higher doses [[dysphoria]] is reported.<ref name=\"PubMed\" />  It is considered to have an abuse profile similar to, but weaker than, [[lorazepam]].<ref name = \"PubMed\">{{cite journal | title = Subjective and behavioral effects of diphenhydramine, lorazepam and methocarbamol: evaluation of abuse liability | journal = Journal of Pharmacology and Experimental Therapeutics | pmid=1501118 | volume=262 | issue = 2 | pages=707\u201320 | vauthors=Preston KL, Wolf B, Guarino JJ, Griffiths RR| year = 1992 }}</ref>\n\n== Interactions ==\nMethocarbamol may inhibit the effects of [[Pyridostigmine|pyridostigmine bromide]].<ref name=FDA2020Label /> Therefore, methocarbamol should be used with caution in those with [[myasthenia gravis]] taking [[Cholinesterase inhibitor|anticholinesterase]] medications.<ref name=FDA2020Label />\n\nMethocarbamol may disrupt certain screening tests as it can cause color interference in laboratory tests for [[5-Hydroxyindoleacetic acid|5-hydroxy-indoleacetic acid (5-HIAA)]] and in urinary testing for [[Vanillylmandelic acid|vanillylmandelic acid (VMA)]] using the Gitlow method.<ref name=FDA2020Label />\n\n==Pharmacology==\n\n=== Mechanism of action ===\nThe mechanism of action of methocarbamol has not currently been established.<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" /> Its effect is thought to be localized to the central nervous system rather than a direct effect on skeletal muscles.<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" /> It has no effect on the motor end plate or the peripheral nerve fiber.<ref name=FDA2020Label /> The efficacy of the medication is likely related to its sedative effect.<ref name=\"AHFS2019\" />\n\n=== Pharmacokinetics ===\nIn healthy individuals, the plasma clearance of methocarbamol ranges between 0.20 and 0.80 L/h/kg.<ref name=FDA2020Label /> The mean plasma elimination half-life ranges between 1 and 2 hours, and the plasma protein binding ranges between 46% and 50%.<ref name=FDA2020Label /> The elimination half-life was longer in the elderly, those with [[kidney]] problems, and those with [[liver]] problems.<ref name=FDA2020Label />\n\n=== Metabolism ===\nMethocarbamol is the [[carbamate]] derivative of [[guaifenesin]], but does not produce guaifenesin as a [[metabolite]], because the carbamate bond is not hydrolyzed metabolically;<ref name=\"Liver2017\" /><ref name=FDA2020Label /> it's metabolism is by Phase I ring hydroxylation and ''O''-demethylation, followed by Phase II conjugation.<ref name=FDA2020Label /> All the major metabolites are unhydrolyzed carbamates.<ref>Methocarbamol. In: ''DRUGDEX System'' [intranet database]. Greenwood Village, Colorado: Thomson Healthcare; c1974\u20132009 [cited 2009 Feb 10].</ref><ref name=\"metabolismBruce1971\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Bruce RB, Turnbull LB, Newman JH | title = Metabolism of methocarbamol in the rat, dog, and human | journal = J Pharm Sci | date = Jan 1971 | volume = 60 | issue = 1 | pages = 104\u2013106 | pmid = 5548215 | doi = 10.1002/jps.2600600120}}</ref> Small amounts of unchanged methocarbamol are also excreted in the urine.<ref name=FDA2020Label />\n\n==Society and culture==\nMethocarbamol was approved as a muscle relaxant for acute, painful musculoskeletal conditions in the United States in 1957.<ref name=Liver2017 /> Muscle relaxants are widely used to treat low back pain, one of the most frequent health problems in industrialized countries.<ref name=\":4\" /> Currently, there are more than 3 million prescriptions filled yearly.<ref name=Liver2017 /> Methocarbamol and [[orphenadrine]], are each used in more than 250,000 U.S. emergency department visits for lower back pain each year.<ref name=\":2\" /> In the United States, low back pain is the fifth most common reason for all physician visits and the second most common symptomatic reason.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chou|first=Roger|last2=Huffman|first2=Laurie Hoyt|date=2007-10-02|title=Medications for Acute and Chronic Low Back Pain: A Review of the Evidence for an American Pain Society/American College of Physicians Clinical Practice Guideline|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.7326/0003-4819-147-7-200710020-00008|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|volume=147|issue=7|pages=505|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-147-7-200710020-00008|issn=0003-4819}}</ref> In 80% of primary care visits for low back pain, at least one medication was prescribed at the initial office visit and more than one third were prescribed two or more medications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cherkin|first=D. C.|last2=Wheeler|first2=K. J.|last3=Barlow|first3=W.|last4=Deyo|first4=R. A.|date=1998-03-01|title=Medication use for low back pain in primary care|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9530793|journal=Spine|volume=23|issue=5|pages=607\u2013614|doi=10.1097/00007632-199803010-00015|issn=0362-2436|pmid=9530793}}</ref> The most commonly prescribed drugs for low back pain included skeletal muscle relaxants.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Luo|first=Xuemei|last2=Pietrobon|first2=Ricardo|last3=Curtis|first3=Lesley H.|last4=Hey|first4=Lloyd A.|date=2004-12-01|title=Prescription of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs and muscle relaxants for back pain in the United States|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15564901|journal=Spine|volume=29|issue=23|pages=E531\u2013537|doi=10.1097/01.brs.0000146453.76528.7c|issn=1528-1159|pmid=15564901}}</ref> [[Cyclobenzaprine]] and methocarbamol are on the U.S. [[Medicare]] formulary, which may account for the higher use of these products.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n===Economics===\nThe generic formulation of the medication is relatively inexpensive costing less than the alternative [[metaxalone]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Robbins |first1=Lawrence D. |title=Management of Headache and Headache Medications |date=2013 |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |isbn=978-1-4612-2124-1 |page=PT147 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Management_of_Headache_and_Headache_Medi/Bmh3BQAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Methocarbamol+inexpensive&pg=PT147 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Fine |first1=Perry G. |title=The Hospice Companion: Best Practices for Interdisciplinary Care of Advanced Illness |date=2016 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-045692-4 |page=PT146 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Hospice_Companion/I7NjDQAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Methocarbamol+cost&pg=PT146 |language=en}}</ref> In the UK costs the [[NHS]] pay about \u00a313 for 100 tablets of 750 mg of methocarbamol as of 2019.<ref name=BNF76>{{cite book|title=British national formulary : BNF 76|date=2018|publisher=Pharmaceutical Press|isbn=9780857113382|pages=1093|edition=76}}</ref> In the US the [[NADAC|wholesale cost]] of this quantity is about US$10 as of 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=NADAC as of 2020-04-15 {{!}} Data.Medicaid.gov |url=https://data.medicaid.gov/Drug-Pricing-and-Payment/NADAC-as-of-2020-04-15/rj2z-7f86 |website=Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\n[[File:Methocarbamol 750 MG Oral Tablet.jpg|thumb|Generic methocarbamol 750mg tablet.]]\nMethocarbamol without other ingredients is sold under the brand name Robaxin in the U.K., U.S. and Canada; it is marketed as Lumirelax in France, Ortoton in Germany and many other names worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Methocarbamol|url=https://www.drugs.com/international/methocarbamol.html|website=Drugs.com|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref> In combination with other active ingredients it is sold under other names: with [[acetaminophen]] (Paracetamol), under trade names Robaxacet and Tylenol Body Pain Night; with [[ibuprofen]] as Robax Platinum; with [[acetylsalicylic acid]] as Robaxisal in the U.S. and Canada.<ref name=\"ESI\">{{cite web | title = New Drugs and Indications Reviewed at the May 2003 DEC Meeting | publisher = [[Express Scripts Incorporated|ESI Canada]] | url = http://www.esi-canada.com/aboutus/news/health_newsflashes/volume5_issue9_newdrugsmay2003.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate = 2008-11-14 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110710201457/http://www.esi-canada.com/aboutus/news/health_newsflashes/volume5_issue9_newdrugsmay2003.pdf | archivedate = 2011-07-10 }}</ref><ref name=\"Tylenol\">{{cite web | title = Tylenol Body Pain Night Overview and Dosage | publisher = [[Johnson & Johnson|Tylenol Canada]] | url = http://www.tylenol.ca/adult-pain-relief/tylenol-body-pain-night | format = website | accessdate = 2012-04-23 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120331074351/http://www.tylenol.ca/adult-pain-relief/tylenol-body-pain-night | archivedate = 2012-03-31 }}</ref> However, in Spain the tradename Robaxisal is used for the paracetamol combination instead of Robaxacet. These combinations are also available from independent manufacturers under generic names.\n\n== Research ==\nAlthough [[Opioid|opioids]] are a typically first line in treatment of severe pain, research suggests that methocarbamol may improve recovery and decrease hospital length of stay in those with muscles spasms associated with [[Rib fracture|rib fractures]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Patanwala|first=Asad E.|last2=Aljuhani|first2=Ohoud|last3=Kopp|first3=Brian J.|last4=Erstad|first4=Brian L.|date=October 2017|title=Methocarbamol use is associated with decreased hospital length of stay in trauma patients with closed rib fractures|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.amjsurg.2017.01.003|journal=The American Journal of Surgery|volume=214|issue=4|pages=738\u2013742|doi=10.1016/j.amjsurg.2017.01.003|issn=0002-9610|via=}}</ref> However, methocarbamol was less useful in the treatment of acute traumatic pain in general.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Aljuhani|first=Ohoud|last2=Kopp|first2=Brian J.|last3=Patanwala|first3=Asad E.|date=2017|title=Effect of Methocarbamol on Acute Pain After Traumatic Injury|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1097/mjt.0000000000000364|journal=American Journal of Therapeutics|volume=24|issue=2|pages=e202\u2013e206|doi=10.1097/mjt.0000000000000364|issn=1075-2765}}</ref>\n\nMethocarbamol has also been suggested to be a safe and well-tolerated medication in the treatment of muscle cramps in those with [[Cirrhosis|liver cirrhosis]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abd-Elsalam|first=Sherief|last2=Arafa|first2=Mona|last3=Elkadeem|first3=Mahmoud|last4=Elfert|first4=Asem|last5=Soliman|first5=Shaimaa|last6=Elkhalawany|first6=Walaa|last7=Badawi|first7=Rehab|date=April 2019|title=Randomized-controlled trial of methocarbamol as a novel treatment for muscle cramps in cirrhotic patients|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30444744|journal=European Journal of Gastroenterology & Hepatology|volume=31|issue=4|pages=499\u2013502|doi=10.1097/MEG.0000000000001310|issn=1473-5687|pmid=30444744|via=}}</ref>\n\nA randomized, double-blind, placebo controlled trial of oral [[naproxen]] with or without methocarbamol or [[orphenadrine]] for acute lower back pain showed the combination of either muscle relaxant with naproxen did not improve functional outcomes compared to naproxen combined placebo.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Friedman|first=Benjamin W.|last2=Cisewski|first2=David|last3=Irizarry|first3=Eddie|last4=Davitt|first4=Michelle|last5=Solorzano|first5=Clemencia|last6=Nassery|first6=Adam|last7=Pearlman|first7=Scott|last8=White|first8=Deborah|last9=Gallagher|first9=E. John|date=March 2018|title=A Randomized, Double-Blind, Placebo-Controlled Trial of Naproxen With or Without Orphenadrine or Methocarbamol for Acute Low Back Pain|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29089169|journal=Annals of Emergency Medicine|volume=71|issue=3|pages=348\u2013356.e5|doi=10.1016/j.annemergmed.2017.09.031|issn=1097-6760|pmc=5820149|pmid=29089169|via=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chlorphenesin]]\n* [[Mephenesin]]\n* [[Mephenoxalone]]\n* [[Metaxalone]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Muscle relaxants}}\n\n[[Category:RTT]]\n[[Category:Muscle relaxants]]\n[[Category:Veterinary drugs]]\n[[Category:Carbamates]]\n[[Category:Catechol ethers]]\n[[Category:Secondary alcohols]]\n[[Category:Drugs with unknown mechanisms of action]]\n", "name_user": "DocWock", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated FDA label to more accurately reflect source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Methocarbamol"}
